replies.bodyText:
Sure is a reason.
You'll note that first I setup so called 'baseQueries', and then I build the other functions off that. Having the two interfaces allows me to build up the first (without the need for optionals) and then build up the other.
For example, say I had:
interface SomeInterface {
  a: () => HTMLElement | null;
  b: () => HTMLElement
}
How do I then build that object such that b is created based on a. AFAIK I can't do:
return {
  a: () => {container.querySelector('body');
  b: () => {
    const e = a();
    if( !e ) {
      throw new Error("no e");
    }

    return e;
  }
}
???
As for the comment, you are correct. I could work these more.

